.source`"],[1484,"`workflow`"],[886,"`workflows`"],[8,"<Card title=\"Concepts\" href=\"./concepts\" description=\"Workflows, runs, runners, approvals, and the Hub's durable record.\" />"],[9,"<Card title=\"HTTP API\" href=\"./guides/api\" description=\"Drive Runyard from any language with bearer-token auth and openapi.json.\" />"],[10,"<Card title=\"MCP\" href=\"./guides/mcp\" description=\"Connect AI agents to your Hub with the runyard-mcp server.\" />"],[7,"<Card title=\"Quickstart\" href=\"./quickstart\" description=\"Install the Hub, start a runner, and run your first workflow.\" />"],[13,"1\\. Install the Hub"],[227,"10 / minute"],[14,"2\\. Sign in with the bootstrap token"],[15,"3\\. Install the CLI and log in"],[229,"30 / minute"],[423,"32-byte key (base64/hex) for the encrypted secrets store. Keep it safe — rotating it makes stored secrets unreadable"],[16,"4\\. Start a runner"],[616,"401 / 403 responses"],[17,"5\\. Run the hello workflow"],[18,"6\\. Watch the run and read the results"],[231,"60 / minute"],[233,"60 / minute"],[836,"A **board** is a durable, configured view over work items: lane definitions in operator language, an optional project scope, and the workflows it suggests launching from tickets. Boards make the Work surface (`/app#work`) a **software factory**: tickets are the durable asks, workflows execute them, and linked runs move tickets across the board as they progress."],[990,"A **post-run hook profile** is an admin-authored recipe for an optional side effect — publishing static output, pushing a work branch, calling a webhook — that runs *after* a run has produced its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."],[1155,"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."],[1112,"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."],[1240,"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."],[880,"A **transition** is a cross-lane move on the board (e.g. Ready → In motion). By default every move a work-item PATCH proposes is allowed — that's what today's Work board does. Adding a `transitions[]` entry to a lane turns it into an **allow-list**: the move is permitted only when the caller matches one of the listed channels."],[1394,"A **work item*&#x2A; (ticket) is the durable unit of company work: &#x2A;\"Make pause/resume fully supported\"&#x2A;, &#x2A;\"Fix the flaky release gate\"*. It is deliberately distinct from the two execution concepts:"],[1492,"A **workflow package** is a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` file for moving a workflow between Hubs. Exports contain source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content/workflow hashes — never secret values. Imports publish the source as a new immutable bundle and create the workflow **disabled by default**, so an admin can configure and preflight it locally before enabling it. `validate` and `preview` let you check a package without writing anything."],[1470,"A **workflow** is the unit of the Runyard catalog: a named, versioned definition of something an agent can do. Each workflow has a slug, a display name and description, input/output schemas, and a source program that the runner executes. In older code and database tables the same object is called a *capability* — that is the legacy/internal synonym; user-facing surfaces say workflow."],[896,"A board **definition** is a portable JSON document describing a whole kanban — lanes, statuses, triggers, guards, transition policy, `defaultWorkflows`, and optional `schedules[]` (see Schedules). Definitions are the write path agents use to provision or reconcile boards; the DB row is one *instance* of a definition."],[789,"A card's `status` is only ever `pending` or `resolved`. What was decided and by what live in separate fields:"],[284,"A creator can make a card timed by supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt`, optionally with a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`) — via `POST /api/approvals` or the `create_approval` MCP tool:"],[1414,"A deliverable exists and needs inspection."],[545,"A deployed Hub checks the public GitHub Releases API passively (outbound-only, `UPDATE_CHECK_ENABLED`, default on) and shows admins an update badge."],[856,"A disabled-by-default schedule, `runyard-daily-roadmap-shaping`, is pinned to `0 9 * * *` in `America/New_York` and runs `product-workflow` with `execute: true`."],[1023,"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."],[223,"A few endpoints are rate-limited per client IP (over the limit returns `429`):"],[780,"A gated side effect asking permission before it runs."],[822,"A held run is cancelled, never failed."],[885,"A human or an authenticated token that hasn't declared a workflow/run origin (the default for any PATCH)."],[858,"A human reviews the resulting branch and explicitly promotes only accepted work into `main`."],[1039,"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."],[74,"A metered, resumable run end to end:"],[677,"A minimal, real example"],[1341,"A normal person or agent: read everything, run workflows, decide approvals. No admin or runner rights."],[1245,"A portable board definition can carry a `schedules[]` array. Importing the definition creates each listed schedule keyed by `board:<slug>:<schedule-slug>` so re-imports reconcile in-place instead of duplicating cron jobs. The optional `laneId` on a definition schedule marks which lane's trigger the schedule backs — the factory template uses it for the \"Ready → In motion\" nightly smoke check. This is the write path a board's lane trigger uses to hook into the existing schedule surface without a second round-trip."],[630,"A quality gate (tests, lint, typecheck, build, eval) failed inside the workflow."],[621,"A queued run means no runner has claimed it — either no runner is online, or none matches the run's required tags / requested location (`local` vs `vps`/`remote`)."],[893,"A role slug: `manual`, `human`, `agent`, `runner`, `schedule`, `workflow`, `system`."],[1396,"a run is **one execution attempt** of a workflow."],[613,"A run is in `waiting_approval`"],[612,"A run is stuck in `queued`"],[1289,"A run receives the union of:"],[1199,"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."],[622,"A runner is considered offline after \\~30 seconds without a heartbeat. If the runner should be online, check its service logs on the runner host:"],[385,"A running Hub also serves its own **client** install script at\n`https://hub.example.com/install.sh` (plus the CLI tarball at `/cli.tgz`). That\none installs the `runyard` CLI and `runyard-mcp` on a workstation — see\nthe CLI guide."],[2,"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."],[954,"A specific artifact."],[891,"A stable actor label: a token name, a run id (`run:<id>`), or a specific caller identity."],[1319,"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."],[1064,"A usage record is one observed model call:"],[1397,"A work item can use one workflow, many workflows, or none yet. Many runs can attach to one work item; a run belongs to at most one work item, and old runs can stay unlinked. Crucially, **there is no failed ticket state** — run failures are execution facts, not ticket verdicts. A failed linked run parks its ticket in `blocked` with an explicit reason (see Boards → Runs move tickets); humans and agents can always re-park or retry."],[1471,"A workflow definition carries:"],[733,"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."],[1395,"a workflow is a reusable **recipe**;"],[776,"A workflow paused at a gate; the decision releases or denies that step."],[887,"A workflow slug — set `workflowSlug` on the PATCH body (or the run whose status change is driving the move)."],[1119,"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."],[211,"Abandon the negotiation"],[507,"Admin & updates"],[660,"Admin actions (creating workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules) need `admin`; running workflows needs `api` or `mcp`; the runner protocol needs `runner`. Ask a Hub admin for a token with the right scopes."],[978,"Admin and setup views."],[1037,"Admin readiness dry-run."],[348,"Admin-scoped commands:"],[1511,"Admin; disables."],[1538,"Admin; imports disabled."],[1535,"Admin; nothing written."],[1449,"Admin; prefer `status: \"archived\"`."],[1387,"Admin; who did what, most recent first."],[743,"Admin."],[746,"Admin."],[751,"Admin."],[754,"Admin."],[760,"Admin."],[763,"Admin."],[1034,"Admin."],[1269,"Admin."],[1272,"Admin."],[1275,"Admin."],[1281,"Admin."],[1308,"Admin."],[1366,"Admin."],[1375,"Admin."],[1508,"Admin."],[1526,"Admin."],[1529,"Admin."],[1532,"Admin."],[1372,"Admin. `{name, scopes, expiresInDays?}`."],[1305,"Admin. `{value, description?}`."],[1266,"Admin. Body: `name`, `workflowSlug`, `cron` or `runAt`, `timezone`, `input`, `enabled`."],[1502,"Admin. Inline source or `workflow.bundleId`."],[1302,"Admin. Names and metadata only."],[1369,"Admin. Scope vocabulary, presets, defaults."],[714,"Admins can export a workflow as a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package file. It contains the workflow source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content hashes — never secret values."],[39,"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."],[717,"Agents, Skills & Knowledge"],[132,"Aliases are the same registry entries registered twice, so they always share\nthe canonical route's handler, auth, and scopes; in `openapi.json` each alias\ncarries `x-canonical-path`. Unversioned `/api/...` paths remain fully\nsupported — use whichever reads better. The legacy `/api/capabilities/*`\npaths are deprecated aliases of `/api/workflows/*` and get no `/api/v1` form;\nnew clients should say *workflow* everywhere."],[905,"All boards, default first."],[732,"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."],[723,"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."],[772,"An **approval** is a declared question with a declared consequence, presented to a human as a card in the web app, over Telegram, or through the API/MCP. Cards can hold a run before it executes (`waiting_approval`), pause a workflow mid-run at an engine gate, or simply record a decision. A run held on an approval waits indefinitely — waiting never fails it."],[246,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[788,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is treated as absent; such cards fall back to a heuristic ask explicitly marked `derived: true`, so a guessed question is never presented as an authored one."],[1083,"An invalid budget is rejected with `400 budget_invalid` at creation (and surfaces as a preflight blocker in negotiation) — a requested cap is never silently dropped."],[389,"And the runner unit (`deploy/runyard-runner.service`):"],[207,"Answer questions: `input` is shallow-merged (a `null` value deletes a key; `replaceInput: true` replaces it), then re-preflighted"],[782,"Any ad-hoc approval raised via the API."],[914,"Any subset; `slug` is immutable."],[1446,"Any subset; move lanes by setting `status`."],[722,"API & MCP"],[771,"API & MCP"],[835,"API & MCP"],[989,"API & MCP"],[1111,"API & MCP"],[1154,"API & MCP"],[1239,"API & MCP"],[1286,"API & MCP"],[1316,"API & MCP"],[1393,"API & MCP"],[1469,"API & MCP"],[81,"API groups and `/api/v1` aliases"],[272,"Applied as a deny with your note attached; the workflow's own deny path decides what happens next."],[273,"Applied as a deny; the workflow's deny path decides what happens next."],[765,"Approval cards - kinds, the ask contract, resolutions, timed approvals with fallbacks, and per-kind consequences."],[981,"Approval cards carry `deepLink` (the card) and `deepLinkRun` (the linked run), and their `context` includes workflow and run deep links."],[244,"Approval cards with buttons"],[564,"Approval gating"],[970,"Approval inbox / one card."],[1347,"Approval inboxes and bots that only decide."],[84,"Approvals"],[312,"Approvals"],[483,"Approvals"],[764,"Approvals"],[38,"Approvals — put human checkpoints in front of dangerous work."],[236,"Approvals and Telegram"],[283,"Approvals are blocking by default: with no timer configured, nothing happens until someone decides, and a linked run is held open indefinitely."],[1381,"Approvals-scoped Telegram session."],[263,"Approve"],[194,"Approve — a held run is released"],[1357,"Approving from Telegram uses `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp&#x60;, which verifies Telegram's signed init data against the configured bot and allowlisted users, then issues a session scoped to **`approvals` only** — narrower than any token session. A Telegram session can list and resolve approval cards but cannot start runs or touch admin surfaces."],[485,"Artifacts"],[66,"Ask the Hub's administrator for a scoped access token (admins issue them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`). Agents typically need `api` and/or `mcp` — nothing more. Send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every HTTP call, or configure it for the MCP server. Never ask for or expect the bootstrap/admin token."],[509,"Assistant"],[1424,"Attach runs three ways:"],[181,"Audit log (admin)"],[50,"Auth"],[44,"Auth expectations"],[78,"Authenticate, discover, and drive workflow runs over the Runyard Hub's HTTP API."],[79,"Authentication"],[674,"Authoring workflows"],[37,"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."],[778,"Autonomous recovery gave up; a human records how to proceed."],[448,"Back this directory up. The runner workspace, by contrast, is disposable\nscratch space — outputs and event traces are uploaded to the Hub as artifacts."],[1310,"Bearer-token authentication, the scope vocabulary and presets (including read-only), the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."],[1190,"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard ca