ary, and inline buttons: **Approve**, **Request changes**, **Reject**. Only the configured approval user ids can act; a button press resolves the card exactly like the web or API would, and the message is edited to show the resolution (\"Approved by ... at ...\") with the buttons removed."],[991,"Each profile has a fixed `kind` with a fixed set of config keys — anything else is rejected, so raw credentials or ad-hoc shell fragments can never be smuggled into a profile:"],[1122,"Each runner declares a `capacity` (concurrent run slots) and reports its active runs; the Hub assigns work only to free slots. `GET /api/runners` returns every registered runner with heartbeat state, capacity, active slots, plus a pool summary — the same data the **Runners** page in the web app shows (`#runners`)."],[1249,"Each schedule tracks `nextRunAt`, `lastRunAt`, the last run id, and the last run's current terminal status, all visible on the Schedules page (`#schedules`) and in the API. Enabled schedules must target an enabled workflow. If a workflow is disabled later, RunYard fails safe: dependent enabled schedules are atomically auto-disabled, keep their history, and expose `state: \"broken\"`, `brokenReason`, `disabledReason`, and `operatorAction` in API/MCP/Web payloads. Re-enable only after editing the schedule to an enabled workflow."],[968,"Edit the workflow (admin)."],[993,"Effect"],[859,"Enable the schedule only on a Hub where daily proposal runs are desired. Importing the definition in tests or dev keeps it disabled so it cannot create unsolicited runs."],[1236,"Enable, disable, run now"],[1468,"Enabled and disabled"],[177,"Encrypted secrets store — names and metadata only, never values (admin)"],[224,"Endpoint"],[570,"Endpoint"],[736,"Endpoint"],[805,"Endpoint"],[900,"Endpoint"],[1024,"Endpoint"],[1124,"Endpoint"],[1200,"Endpoint"],[1253,"Endpoint"],[1297,"Endpoint"],[1358,"Endpoint"],[1432,"Endpoint"],[1494,"Endpoint"],[894,"Enforcement runs on **every board whose project scope covers the ticket**. A denial from any board rejects the PATCH with `409 Conflict`, the board's `message`, and the offending `{from, to}` transition. Callers driving a move on behalf of a workflow or run should declare it on the PATCH body:"],[366,"Environment variables"],[323,"Environment variables `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` (and an explicit\n`--url` / `--token`) take precedence over the saved remote."],[86,"Error conventions"],[1151,"Events, timeline, logs, artifacts"],[1085,"Every budgeted run also carries a computed &#x2A;*`budgetStatus`** — spent vs limit, per dimension — so no client re-derives the arithmetic:"],[799,"Every card answers \"what will my decision do\" honestly, computed from what resolving actually performs:"],[1098,"Every claude / codex / pi CLI call the Smithers engine reports via its structured `TokenUsageReported` events"],[837,"Every deployment seeds one default board on first boot — &#x2A;\"\\<instance name> Factory\"* (slug `runyard` by default) — so the Work view is a configured product surface from day one, never an empty shell. More boards can be created for product, infra, docs, or release trains."],[1250,"Every fire dispatches a normal run whose origin identifies the schedule:"],[113,"Every grouped operation is also reachable at a stable `/api/v1` alias that\nmakes the group visible in the path — for example:"],[939,"Every Hub URL is shareable - the hash-route grammar of the web app and the deep links the API returns."],[569,"Every operation requires either a bearer access token (`Authorization: Bearer ...`) or a browser session created by exchanging such a token — and the session carries exactly the token's scopes, no extra power. The unauthenticated surface is deliberately tiny:"],[532,"Every PR and push to `main` (and tags)"],[1063,"Every run durably records not just what it produced, but **what it consumed**. Each model call a run's child agents make is captured as a usage record, streamed as a run event while the