chable over the API too. YAML is a future syntax; JSON is the documented format today."],[320,"The fastest path is the install script served by your own Hub, which downloads\nthe CLI tarball from the same instance (`/cli.tgz`), installs `runyard` and\n`runyard-mcp` into `~/.local/bin`, and logs you in:"],[1059,"The fleet rollup: `GET /api/usage/summary`"],[1431,"The fold is derived, never stored: explicit `node.*` lifecycle events win; an unresolved `engine.approval.waiting` parks its step in `waiting`; the run's own terminal status closes the books (succeeded finishes unfinished active steps, cancelled cancels them, a failure-terminal status fails the step the run died on). When no source graph exists the flow degrades to an event-derived stepper rather than hiding observed work. The ticket detail renders this as the flow view for the active or latest linked run."],[57,"The full HTTP surface, generated from the Hub's API surface registry — it cannot drift from the routes the server actually registers."],[279,"The gated side effect is allowed to run."],[527,"The GitHub Actions pipeline (`.github/workflows/release.yml` and `images.yml`) has four jobs:"],[267,"The held run is released to the queue and executes."],[1022,"The hook did not run."],[288,"The Hub can post approval cards to a Telegram chat and accept decisions from the buttons on them."],[405,"The Hub is a single HTTP listener; any TLS-terminating proxy that forwards **all\npaths** to the Hub port works. With Caddy:"],[386,"The Hub listens on `127.0.0.1:43117` by default. Start a runner in a second\nprocess:"],[376,"The Hub uses the built-in `node:sqlite` module (started with `--experimental-sqlite`)"],[897,"The importer is idempotent: creating on new slugs, updating when the slug exists, and reconciling `schedules[]` by slug so re-imports never duplicate cron jobs. A production-ready example ships in the repo at `workflow-templates/board-definitions/runyard-development-factory.json`; fetch the same document